description.narrative: By 2023, national and sub-national health system and service providers have improved capacity to deliver quality nutrition- specific interventions., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Early Childhood Development, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition (Covid), Sanitation, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023 pregnant women, mothers, newborns and children under the age of 5 years have increased equitable access to and the use of quality health and nutrition services, especially in the north-eastern provinces and among marginalized groups, including during emergencies.

description.narrative: Despite the COVID-19 pandemic, the continuity of high impact MIYCN services was maintained by the Government, including in UNICEF supported areas. UNICEF was able to leverage COVID-19 resources and efforts to strengthen IYCF promotion. While the management of SAM was maintained and integrated outreach services with immunization was conducted safely during the pandemic, the overall SAM programme could not be scaled-up due to lack of funding. UNICEF strengthened its collaboration with SUN network partners, which resulted in joint high-level advocacy on food security and nutrition in Cambodia given COVID-19, building upon global and regional advocacy efforts. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:26/08/2020
